gobblin.source.extractor.extract.kafka.workunit.packer

Class KafkaBiLevelWorkUnitPacker

  • java.lang.Object
    • gobblin.source.extractor.extract.kafka.workunit.packer.KafkaWorkUnitPacker
      • gobblin.source.extractor.extract.kafka.workunit.packer.KafkaBiLevelWorkUnitPacker

  • public class KafkaBiLevelWorkUnitPacker
extends KafkaWorkUnitPacker
    An implementation of KafkaWorkUnitPacker with two levels of bin packing. In the first level, some WorkUnits corresponding to partitions of the same topic are grouped together into a single WorkUnit. The number of grouped WorkUnits is approximately WORKUNIT_PRE_GROUPING_SIZE_FACTOR * number of MultiWorkUnits. The value of WORKUNIT_PRE_GROUPING_SIZE_FACTOR should generally be 3.0 or higher, since the worst-fit-decreasing algorithm (used by the second level) may not achieve a good balance if the number of items is less than 3 times the number of bins. In the second level, these grouped WorkUnits are assembled into MultiWorkunits using worst-fit-decreasing. Bi-level bin packing has two advantages: (1) reduce the number of small output files since it tends to pack partitions of the same topic together; (2) reduce the total number of workunits / tasks since multiple partitions of the same topic are assigned to the same task. A task has a non-trivial cost of initialization, tear down and task state persistence. However, bi-level bin packing has more mapper skew than single-level bin packing, because if we pack lots of partitions of the same topic to the same mapper, and we underestimate the avg time per record for this topic, then this mapper could be much slower than other mappers.
